data.Meaning: adjective: complete and wholly (usually modifying a noun with negative connotation)
data.Example: An arrant fool, Lawrence surprised nobody when he lost all his money in a pyramid scheme that was every bit as transparent as it was corrupt.

data.Meaning: adjective: irritable and is likely to cause disruption
data.Example: We rarely invite my fractious Uncle over for dinner; he always complains about the food, and usually launches into a tirade on some touchy subject.

data.Meaning: adjective: weighed-down; moving slowly
data.Example: Laden with 20 kilograms of college text books, the freshman moved ponderously across the campus.

data.Meaning: verb: to intimidate
data.Example: Do not be cowed by a 3,000-word vocabulary list: turn that list into a deck of flashcards!

data.Meaning: adjective: intolerable, difficult to endure
data.Example: Chester always tried to find some area in which he excelled above others; unsurprisingly, his co-workers found him insufferable and chose to exclude him from daily luncheons out.

data.Meaning: noun: an eager willingness to do something
data.Example: The first three weeks at his new job, Mark worked with such alacrity that upper management knew it would be giving him a promotion.

data.Meaning: adjective: done routinely and with little interest or care
data.Example: The short film examines modern perfunctory cleaning rituals such as washing dishes, doing laundry and tooth-brushing.

data.Meaning: verb: to eliminate completely
data.Example: When I turned 18, all of the shoplifting and jaywalking charges were expunged from my criminal record.

data.Meaning: noun: critical explanation or analysis, especially of a text
data.Example: The Bible is fertile ground for exegesis—over the past five centuries there have been as many interpretations as there are pages in the Old Testament.

data.Meaning: noun: depravity; a depraved act
data.Example: During his reign, Caligula indulged in unspeakable sexual practices, so it is not surprising that he will forever be remembered for his turpitude.

data.Meaning: adjective: hasty or rash
data.Example: Instead of conducting a thorough investigation after the city hall break-in, the governor acted precipitately, accusing his staff of aiding and abetting the criminals.

data.Meaning: adjective: produced by, or characterized by internal dissension
data.Example: The controversial bill proved factious, as dissension even within parties resulted

data.Meaning: adjective: lecherous; sexually perverted
data.Example: Lolita is a challenging novel for many, not necessarily because of the elevated prose style but because of the depravity of the main character, Humbert Humbert, who, as an old, lascivious man, lusts after a girl.

data.Meaning: noun: spirit of the times

data.Meaning: noun: exaltation to divine status; the highest point of development
data.Example: As difficult as it is to imagine, the apotheosis of Mark Zuckerberg’s career, many believe, is yet to come.

data.Meaning: noun: a person who indulges in luxury
data.Example: Despite the fact that he’d maxed out fifteen credit cards, Max was still a sybarite at heart: when the police found him, he was at a $1,000 an hour spa in Manhattan, getting a facial treatment.

data.Meaning: adjective: trifling or petty (a person)

data.Meaning: adjective: bossy and domineering
data.Example: My sister used to peremptorily tell me to do the dishes, a chore I would either do perfunctorily or avoid doing altogether.

data.Meaning: adjective: readily taking on different roles; versatile
data.Example: Peter Sellers was truly a protean actor—in Doctor Strangelove he played three very different roles: a jingoist general, a sedate President and a deranged scientist.

data.Meaning: adjective: filled with courage or valor
data.Example: For its raid on the Bin Laden’s compound in Abbottabad, Seal Team Six has become, for many Americans, the embodiment of mettle.

data.Meaning: adjective: likely to lean towards a controversial view
data.Example: Because political mudslinging has become a staple of the 24-hour media cycle, most of us, despite protestations to the contrary, are tendentious on many of today’s pressing issues.

data.Meaning: noun: abusive or denunciatory language
data.Example: The Internet has unleashed the invectives in many of us; many people post stinging criticism on the comments section underneath newspaper articles or YouTube videos.

data.Meaning: adjective: overly emotional and sad
data.Example: Just as those who were alive during the 70’s are mortified that they once cavorted about in bellbottoms, many who lived during the 80’s are now aghast at the maudlin pop songs they used to enjoy—really, just what exactly is a total eclipse of the heart?

data.Meaning: noun: a person who has recently reached a position of power; a social climber
data.Example: The city center was aflutter with arrivistes who tried to outdo one another with their ostentatious sports cars and chic evening dress.

data.Meaning: noun: greed for money
data.Example: Some people believe that amassing as much wealth as possible is the meaning to life—yet they often realize that cupidity brings anything but happiness.

data.Meaning: adjective: illusive; unreal

data.Meaning: adjective: smooth and sweet-sounding
data.Example: Chelsea’s grandmother thought Franz Schubert’s music to be the most mellifluous ever written; Chelsea demurred, and to her grandmother’s chagrin, would blast Rihanna on the home stereo speakers.

data.Meaning: verb: to criticize very harshly
data.Example: Entrusted with the prototype to his company’s latest smartphone, Larry, during a late night karaoke bout, let the prototype slip into the hands of a rival company—the next day Larry was excoriated, and then fired.

data.Meaning: adjective: irritable; always angry

data.Meaning: verb: to limit or qualify a statement; to avoid making a direct statement
data.Example: When asked why he had decided to buy millions of shares at the very moment the tech company's stock soared, the CEO hedged, mentioning something vague about gut instinct.

data.Meaning: adjective: to be moralizing, usually in a pompous sense
data.Example: The old man, casting his nose up in the air at the group of adolescents, intoned sententiously, “Youth is wasted on the young.”

data.Meaning: adjective: easily excused or forgiven; pardonable
data.Example: His traffic violations ran the gamut from the venial to the egregious—on one occasion he simply did not come to a complete stop; another time he tried to escape across state lines at speeds in excess of 140 mph.

data.Meaning: noun: the confusion of a word with another word that sounds similar
data.Example: Whenever I looked glum, my mother would offer to share "an amusing antidote" with me—an endearing malapropism of "anecdote" that never failed to cheer me up.

data.Meaning: noun: a person who has suddenly become wealthy, but not socially accepted as part of a higher class
data.Example: The theater was full of parvenus who each thought that they were surrounded by true aristocrats.

data.Meaning: adjective: describing a victory that comes at such a great cost that the victory is not worthwhile

data.Meaning: adjective: to have a limited outlook or understanding

data.Meaning: adjective: fallen into a state of ignorance

data.Meaning: noun: A resource available to students to help them study for the GRE. Learn more at http://gre.magoosh.com
data.Example: Chris did well on the GRE after learning from over 200 Magoosh video lessons.

data.Meaning: adjective: artificial; not natural

data.Meaning: adjective: having clarity in terms of expression

data.Meaning: noun: joy from watching the suffering of others

data.Meaning: noun: calmness or poise in difficult situations

data.Meaning: adjective: dull; lacking flavor

data.Meaning: verb: to criticize harshly; to berate

data.Meaning: verb: to make objections while pleading

data.Meaning: noun: a grouchy, surly person

data.Meaning: adjective: to be biased against due to envy or prejudice
data.Example: Shelly was jaundiced towards Olivia; though the two had once been best friends, Olivia had become class president, prom queen, and, to make matters worse, the girlfriend of the one boy Shelly liked.

data.Meaning: adjective: wildly idealistic; impractical

data.Meaning: verb: to curse and hiss at

data.Meaning: noun: a strict disciplinarian

data.Meaning: adjective: to be deliberately teasing

data.Meaning: adjective: lacking money; poor

data.Meaning: adjective: extremely optimistic

data.Meaning: verb: to persuade somebody that his/her belief is not valid

data.Meaning: adjective: related to fashion or clothes

data.Meaning: noun: a traitor

data.Meaning: verb: to defraud or swindle

data.Meaning: noun: something that has been changed numerous times but on which traces of former iterations can still be seen

data.Meaning: noun: a force that cannot be stopped

data.Meaning: adjective: terribly evil

data.Meaning: verb: to manipulate voting districts in order to favor a particular political party

data.Meaning: adjective: to be overly theatrical

data.Meaning: verb: to remove objectionable material

data.Meaning: verb: to placate or appease

data.Meaning: verb: attribute (responsibility or fault) to something
data.Example: He imputed his subpar performance on the test to a combination of stress and poor sleep.

data.Meaning: adjective: biting and caustic in thought, manner, or style

data.Meaning: adjective: ominously prophetic

data.Meaning: verb: enthusiastically acclaim or celebrate something

data.Meaning: adjective: excessively flattering toward someone's life or work

data.Meaning: verb: wander aimlessly

data.Meaning: adjective: (of a person) not doing one's duties

data.Meaning: noun: a statement made about the future

data.Meaning: adjective: relating to or involving money

data.Meaning: adjective: marked by courage and determination
